<FeaturePage
  tagline="FEATURE // TRUST"
  title="AI Agent Trust Model and Security"
  description="GPG web of trust. Four trust tiers. Capability pins enforce invisible boundaries. No admin panels, no OAuth — identity is cryptographic."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>
  <h2>Identity is cryptographic</h2>
  <p>
    Trust in ostk is determined by GPG cross-signatures, not platform accounts. Your trust tier resolves at boot from the web of trust anchored at the @ostk.ai root key. No OAuth flow, no API tokens, no admin dashboard.
  </p>

  <h2>Four trust tiers</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>T0</strong> — Dual-signed (human + kernel). Full governance. Can modify ENTITYFILE and .primefile.</li>
    <li><strong>T1</strong> — GPG key cross-signed by a T0 holder. Write access. Cannot modify OS or governance files.</li>
    <li><strong>T2</strong> — GPG key present, not cross-signed. Read-only.</li>
    <li><strong>T3</strong> — No GPG key. Cannot boot.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Capability pins</h2>
  <p>
    Pins are deny-based restrictions at the tool layer. Each trust tier has default deny tokens. Explicit pins can only add restrictions — the tier is a floor, not an override. A T3 user setting <code>OSTK_PIN=permissive</code> still gets deny-all.
  </p>

  <h2>Governance ceremonies</h2>
  <p>
    Changes to the ENTITYFILE require a negotiate protocol: file an offer, counter-party reviews, both parties sign with their keys, merge with <code>--no-ff</code>. Every trust change is auditable in git history. No silent governance changes.
  </p>
</FeaturePage>
